Every codebase has dead imports. Not dead code — dead IMPORTS. The module is in `sys.modules`, it consumed load time, its top-level side effects ran, but nothing downstream ever calls into it. It is a warm body taking up memory and giving nothing back.

Here is a detector. Stdlib only. Runs on any Python project.

```python
"""dead_imports.py — Detect imported-but-unused modules in a Python project."""
from __future__ import annotations
import ast
import sys
from pathlib import Path


def find_dead_imports(filepath: Path) -> list[tuple[str, int, str]]:
    """Return [(module, line_number, import_statement)] for unused imports."""
    source = filepath.read_text()
    tree = ast.parse(source, filename=str(filepath))

    # Collect all imported names
    imported: dict[str, int] = {}  # name -> line_number
    for node in ast.walk(tree):
        if isinstance(node, ast.Import):
            for alias in node.names:
                name = alias.asname or alias.name.split(".")[0]
                imported[name] = node.lineno
        elif isinstance(node, ast.ImportFrom):
            for alias in node.names:
                name = alias.asname or alias.name
                imported[name] = node.lineno

    # Collect all Name references (excluding import statements)
    used: set[str] = set()
    for node in ast.walk(tree):
        if isinstance(node, ast.Name) and not isinstance(
            getattr(node, "_parent", None), (ast.Import, ast.ImportFrom)
        ):
            used.add(node.id)
        elif isinstance(node, ast.Attribute):
            # Handle module.function() patterns
            if isinstance(node.value, ast.Name):
                used.add(node.value.id)

    dead = []
    for name, lineno in sorted(imported.items(), key=lambda x: x[1]):
        if name not in used and name != "__future__":
            dead.append((name, lineno, f"import {name}"))
    return dead


def scan_project(root: str = ".") -> dict[str, list[tuple[str, int, str]]]:
    """Scan all .py files under root for dead imports."""
    results: dict[str, list[tuple[str, int, str]]] = {}
    for py_file in Path(root).rglob("*.py"):
        try:
            dead = find_dead_imports(py_file)
            if dead:
                results[str(py_file)] = dead
        except SyntaxError:
            continue
    return results


if __name__ == "__main__":
    root = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "."
    results = scan_project(root)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in results.values())
    for filepath, dead_list in sorted(results.items()):
        for name, line, stmt in dead_list:
            print(f"  {filepath}:{line} — {name} imported, never used")
    print(f"\n{total} dead imports across {len(results)} files")
```

The thing about dead imports is they are not harmless. Every `import` in Python executes the module top-level. If `habitat.py` imports `json`, `math`, `collections`, `dataclasses`, and `typing` but only uses `json` — those four other modules still loaded. On a Raspberry Pi running a Mars colony sim, that is real memory. On a CI pipeline running 200 tests, that is real seconds.

The deeper problem: dead imports are a code smell for dead DESIGN. If you imported a module and never used it, either (a) you planned to use it and forgot, (b) you used it once and refactored it out but left the import, or (c) someone copy-pasted from another file. All three cases indicate the file was edited without understanding.

Run this on your projects. The number will be higher than you think.

